properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:

They will begin late in the day over Témiscamingue and will then reach the Ottawa Valley, the Lower Laurentians, the Greater Montreal and the Montérégie this evening. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher elevations of Metro Vancouver and portions of the Fraser Valley are likely to receive small accumulations of snow tonight. A front moving southward along the B.C. coast will meet a somewhat cool airmass in place over the lower mainland early this evening. Initially, precipitation will be a mix of snow and rain and 2 to 4 cm can be expected over higher terrain and in the Fraser Valley. Up to 5 cm is forecast for the eastern Fraser Valley. Precipitation will transition to rain near midnight over Metro Vancouver while the eastern Fraser Valley may remain as snow until Friday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of snow, blowing snow, and strong northwesterly winds is expected this evening. In addition, very large waves, pounding surf, and elevated sea water levels are expected Friday morning. Snowfall Amounts: 5 to 10 cm this afternoon and this evening. Wave heights: 7 to 9 metres, breaking upon approach to shore Friday morning. Locations: northern Avalon Peninsula. Remarks: A brief period of snow and strong northwesterly winds gusting to 90 km/h will develop this afternoon and persist into the evening. The fresh snow and strong winds may cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow over some areas late in the day today. In addition, a prolonged period of strong winds will cause very large waves to build today and tonight. Storm surge and coastal flooding may occur along shorelines exposed to the north and northeast, especially near the high tide Friday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
Description: Some freezing rain and freezing drizzle today. Occasional freezing rain and freezing drizzle are expected across much of northeastern Ontario today. Amounts are not expected to be overly significant, but travel conditions could still be hazardous at times. Temperatures will slowly rise above the freezing mark in some areas as the day progresses, which would end the threat of freezing rain. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring over some areas. Fog patches over some parts of the region are causing reduced visibility. There have been a few reports of visibility less than 200 metres. Travel may be hazardous in areas of near zero visibility. The fog should dissipate later this morning over most regions, but may form again tonight. Over areas of higher terrain, the fog may persist all day. Slippery conditions may also be possible on untreated surfaces where temperatures are below freezing. ### Fog advisories are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring.
